SP  - 2817
EP  - 2858
VL  - 63
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01414.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Using a large sample of partial block acquisitions, we examine the importance of geographic proximity in corporate governance and target returns. We find that block acquirers have a strong preference for geographically proximate targets and acquirers that purchase shares in such targets are more likely to engage in post-acquisition target governance activities than are remote block acquirers. Moreover, the targets of these acquirers realize higher announcement returns and better post-acquisition operating performance than do targets of other types of acquirers, particularly when they face greater information asymmetries.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Estimating the Intertemporal Risk–Return Tradeoff Using the Implied Cost of Capital
AU  - PÁSTOR, ĽUBOŠ
AU  - SINHA, MEENAKSHI
AU  - SWAMINATHAN, BHASKARAN
Y1  - 2008/12/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01415.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2859
EP  - 2897
VL  - 63
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01415.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We argue that the implied cost of capital (ICC), computed using earnings forecasts, is useful in capturing time variation in expected stock returns. First, we show theoretically that ICC is perfectly correlated with the conditional expected stock return under plausible conditions. Second, our simulations show that ICC is helpful in detecting an intertemporal risk?return relation, even when earnings forecasts are poor. Finally, in empirical analysis, we construct the time series of ICC for the G?7 countries. We find a positive relation between the conditional mean and variance of stock returns, at both the country level and the world market level.
ER  - 

