T1  - In Search of Distress Risk
AU  - CAMPBELL, JOHN Y.
AU  - HILSCHER, JENS
AU  - SZILAGYI, JAN
Y1  - 2008/12/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01416.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2899
EP  - 2939
VL  - 63
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01416.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper explores the determinants of corporate failure and the pricing of financially distressed stocks whose failure probability, estimated from a dynamic logit model using accounting and market variables, is high. Since 1981, financially distressed stocks have delivered anomalously low returns. They have lower returns but much higher standard deviations, market betas, and loadings on value and small-cap risk factors than stocks with low failure risk. These patterns are more pronounced for stocks with possible informational or arbitrage-related frictions. They are inconsistent with the conjecture that the value and size effects are compensation for the risk of financial distress.
ER  - 

