T1  - How Does Size Affect Mutual Fund Behavior?
AU  - POLLET, JOSHUA M.
AU  - WILSON, MUNGO
Y1  - 2008/12/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01417.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2941
EP  - 2969
VL  - 63
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01417.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT If actively managed mutual funds suffer from diminishing returns to scale, funds should alter investment behavior as assets under management increase. Although asset growth has little effect on the behavior of the typical fund, we find that large funds and small-cap funds diversify their portfolios in response to growth. Greater diversification, especially for small-cap funds, is associated with better performance. Fund family growth is related to the introduction of new funds that hold different stocks from their existing siblings. Funds with many siblings diversify less rapidly as they grow, suggesting that the fund family may influence a fund's portfolio strategy.
ER  - 

